values: If you want something done, ask the busiest person you know.

It's billed as Europe's last wilderness, but here, in this landscape of bog, primeval forest and lakes in deepest Belarus, the only wildlife is a vast cloud of the biggest mosquitos I've ever seen. I don't need Deet. I need a flamethrower.

One could argue that we are currently witnessing a crisis of the traditional aid and international governance models, which could have far-reaching consequences somewhat reminiscent of the dot-com crash. At the same time, the emergence of new approaches (such as microfinance and online campaigning) may herald the beginning of a whole brave new world - indeed, it would seem that the era of the wisdom of crowds and the Long Tail, as defined by O'Reilly, has caught on in the non-profit world. guess what: the more our attention/focus/creativity/productivity become dependent (and even formed) by our online surroundings, the more likely it is that these freaky online-only ideas and stupid buzzwords will enter your mind, life and your office. Not in the form of buzzwords, mind you: but in the form of actions and entities they represent. And yes, even if you happen to work for an NGO or a government agency...
